<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Rules_to_identify_significa=
nt_figures_in_a_number">Rules to identify significant figures in a number</=
h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[<=
/span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSignificant_f=
igures&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: Rules to i=
dentify significant figures in a number"><span>edit</span></a><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:SigFigs.svg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><i=
mg src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/95/SigFigs=
.svg/250px-SigFigs.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"190" height=3D"285"=
 class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"512" data-file-height=3D"768"=
></a><figcaption>Digits in light blue are significant figures; those in bla=
ck are not.</figcaption></figure>
<p>Identifying the significant figures in a number requires knowing which d=
igits are meaningful, which requires knowing the resolution with which the =
number is measured, obtained, or processed. For example, if the measurable =
smallest mass is 0.001&nbsp;g, then in a measurement given as 0.00234&nbsp;=
g the "4" is not useful and should be discarded, while the "3" is useful an=
d should often be retained.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-3" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Significant_figures#cite_note-3"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup>
</p>
<ul><li><b>Non-zero digits within the given measurement or reporting resolu=
tion</b> are <b>significant</b>.
<ul><li>91 has two significant figures (9 and&nbsp;1) if they are measureme=
nt-allowed digits.</li>
<li>123.45 has five significant digits (1, 2, 3, 4 and&nbsp;5) if they are =
within the measurement resolution. If the resolution is, say, 0.1, then the=
 5 shows that the true value to 4 significant figures is equally likely to =
be 123.4 or 123.5.</li></ul></li>
<li><b>Zeros between two significant non-zero digits</b> are <b>significant=
 (<i>significant</i> <i>trapped zeros)</i></b>.
<ul><li>101.12003 consists of eight significant figures if the resolution i=
s to 0.00001.</li>
<li>125.340006 has seven significant figures if the resolution is to 0.0001=
: 1, 2, 5, 3, 4, 0, and&nbsp;0.</li></ul></li>
<li><b>Zeros to the left of the first non-zero digit</b> (<a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leading_zero" title=3D"Leading zero">leading zeros<=
/a>) are <b><u>not</u> significant</b>.
<ul><li>If a length measurement gives <span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sor=
t-value=3D"7001520000000000000=E2=99=A0"></span>0.052&nbsp;km</span>, then =
<span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"7001520000000000000=E2=99=
=A0"></span>0.052&nbsp;km</span> =3D 52&nbsp;m so 5 and 2 are only signific=
ant; the leading zeros appear or disappear, depending on which unit is used=
, so they are not necessary to indicate the measurement scale.</li>
<li>0.00034 has 2 significant figures (3 and&nbsp;4) if the resolution is 0=
.00001.</li></ul></li>
<li><b>Zeros to the right of the last non-zero digit (<a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trailing_zero" title=3D"Trailing zero">trailing zeros</=
a>) in a number with the decimal point</b> are <b>significant</b> if they a=
re within the measurement or reporting resolution.
<ul><li>1.200 has four significant figures (1, 2, 0, and&nbsp;0) if they ar=
e allowed by the measurement resolution.</li>
<li>0.0980 has three significant digits (9, 8, and the last zero) if they a=
re within the measurement resolution.</li>
<li>120.000 consists of six significant figures (1, 2, and the four subsequ=
ent zeroes) if, as before, they are within the measurement resolution.</li>=
</ul></li>
<li><b>Trailing zeros in an integer</b> <b>may or may <u>not</u> be signifi=
cant</b>, depending on the measurement or reporting resolution.
<ul><li><span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"7004456000000000000=
=E2=99=A0"></span>45<span style=3D"margin-left:.25em;">600</span></span> ha=
s 3, 4 or 5 significant figures depending on how the last zeros are used. F=
or example, if the length of a road is reported as 45600&nbsp;m without inf=
ormation about the reporting or measurement resolution, then it is not clea=
r if the road length is precisely measured as 45600&nbsp;m or if it is a ro=
ugh estimate. If it is the rough estimation, then only the first three non-=
zero digits are significant since the trailing zeros are neither reliable n=
or necessary; <span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"7004456000000=
000000=E2=99=A0"></span>45<span style=3D"margin-left:.25em;">600</span>&nbs=
p;m</span> can be expressed as <span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=
=3D"7004456000000000000=E2=99=A0"></span>45.6&nbsp;km</span> or as <span cl=
ass=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"7004455999999999999=E2=99=A0"></spa=
n>4.56<span style=3D"margin-left:0.25em;margin-right:0.15em;">=C3=97</span>=
10<sup>4</sup>&nbsp;m</span> in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sc=
ientific_notation" title=3D"Scientific notation">scientific notation</a>, a=
nd neither expression requires the trailing zeros.</li></ul></li>
<li><b>An exact number has an infinite number of significant figures.</b>
<ul><li>If the number of apples in a bag is 4 (exact number), then this num=
ber is <span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"7000400000000000000=
=E2=99=A0"></span>4.0000...</span> (with infinite trailing zeros to the rig=
ht of the decimal point). As a result, 4&nbsp;does not impact the number of=
 significant figures or digits in the result of calculations with it.</li>
<li>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Planck_constant" title=3D"=
Planck constant">Planck constant</a> is defined as exactly <span class=3D"n=
owrap"><i>h</i> =3D <span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"6966662=
607015000000=E2=99=A0"></span>6.626<span style=3D"margin-left:.25em;">070</=
span><span style=3D"margin-left:.25em;">15</span><span style=3D"margin-left=
:0.25em;margin-right:0.15em;">=C3=97</span>10<sup>=E2=88=9234</sup>&nbsp;J=
=E2=8B=85s</span></span>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Significant_figures#cite_note-4"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p></li></ul></li>
<li><b>A mathematical or physical constant has significant figures to its k=
nown digits.</b>
<ul><li><i>=CF=80</i> is a specific <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Real_number" title=3D"Real number">real number</a> with several equivalen=
t definitions. All of the digits in its exact decimal expansion <span class=
=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"7000314159000000000=E2=99=A0"></span>3=
.141<span style=3D"margin-left:.25em;">59</span>...</span> are significant.=
 Although many properties of these digits are known =E2=80=93 for example, =
they do not repeat, because <i>=CF=80</i> is irrational =E2=80=93 not all o=
f the digits are known. As of March 2024, more than 102&nbsp;trillion digit=
s<sup id=3D"cite_ref-5" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Significant_figures#cite_note-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> have been calculated.=
 A 102 trillion-digit approximation has&nbsp;102 trillion significant digit=
s. In practical applications, far fewer digits are used. The everyday appro=
ximation 3.14 has three significant figures and 7&nbsp;correct <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_number" title=3D"Binary number">binary<=
/a> digits. The approximation 22/7 has the same three correct decimal digit=
s but has 10&nbsp;correct binary digits. Most calculators and computer prog=
rams can handle a 16-digit approximation sufficient for interplanetary navi=
gation calculations.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-NASA/JPL_6-0" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Significant_figures#cite_note-NASA/=
JPL-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup></li></ul></li></ul>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Ways_to_denote_significant_=
figures_in_an_integer_with_trailing_zeros">Ways to denote significant figur=
es in an integer with trailing zeros</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><sp=
an class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/w/index.php?title=3DSignificant_figures&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=
=3D3" title=3D"Edit section: Ways to denote significant figures in an integ=
er with trailing zeros"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-=
bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The significance of trailing zeros in a number not containing a decimal =
point can be ambiguous. For example, it may not always be clear if the numb=
er 1300 is precise to the nearest unit (just happens coincidentally to be a=
n exact multiple of a hundred) or if it is only shown to the nearest hundre=
ds due to rounding or uncertainty. Many conventions exist to address this i=
ssue. However, these are not universally used and would only be effective i=
f the reader is familiar with the convention:
</p>
<ul><li>An <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Overline" title=3D"Over=
line">overline</a>, sometimes also called an overbar, or less accurately, a=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vinculum_(symbol)" title=3D"Vincu=
lum (symbol)">vinculum</a>, may be placed over the last significant figure;=
 any trailing zeros following this are insignificant. For example, 13<span =
style=3D"text-decoration:overline;">0</span>0 has three significant figures=
 (and hence indicates that the number is precise to the nearest ten).</li>
<li>Less often, using a closely related convention, the last significant fi=
gure of a number may be <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Underline"=
 class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Underline">underlined</a>; for example, "1<=
span style=3D"text-decoration: underline;">3</span>00" has two significant =
figures.</li>
<li>A decimal point may be placed after the number; for example "1300." ind=
icates specifically that trailing zeros are meant to be significant.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-Chemistry_Significant_Figures_7-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Significant_figures#cite_note-Chemistry_S=
ignificant_Figures-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li></ul>
<p>As the conventions above are not in general use, the following more wide=
ly recognized options are available for indicating the significance of numb=
er with trailing zeros:
</p>
<ul><li>Eliminate ambiguous or non-significant zeros by changing the <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unit_prefix" title=3D"Unit prefix">unit =
prefix</a> in a number with a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unit=
_of_measurement" title=3D"Unit of measurement">unit of measurement</a>. For=
 example, the precision of measurement specified as 1300&nbsp;g is ambiguou=
s, while if stated as 1.30&nbsp;kg it is not. Likewise 0.0123&nbsp;L can be=
 rewritten as 12.3&nbsp;mL.</li>
<li>Eliminate ambiguous or non-significant zeros by using Scientific Notati=
on: For example, 1300 with three significant figures becomes <span class=3D=
"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"7003130000000000000=E2=99=A0"></span>1.30=
<span style=3D"margin-left:0.25em;margin-right:0.15em;">=C3=97</span>10<sup=
>3</sup></span>. Likewise 0.0123 can be rewritten as <span class=3D"nowrap"=
><span data-sort-value=3D"6998123000000000000=E2=99=A0"></span>1.23<span st=
yle=3D"margin-left:0.25em;margin-right:0.15em;">=C3=97</span>10<sup>=E2=88=
=922</sup></span>. The part of the representation that contains the signifi=
cant figures (1.30 or 1.23) is known as the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Significand" title=3D"Significand">significand</a> or mantissa. T=
he digits in the base and exponent (<span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-=
value=3D"7003100000000000000=E2=99=A0"></span>10<sup>3</sup></span> or <spa=
n class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"6998100000000000000=E2=99=A0"><=
/span>10<sup>=E2=88=922</sup></span>) are considered exact numbers so for t=
hese digits, significant figures are irrelevant.</li>
<li>Explicitly state the number of significant figures (the abbreviation s.=
f. is sometimes used): For example "20&nbsp;000 to 2&nbsp;s.f." or "20&nbsp=
;000 (2&nbsp;sf)".</li>
<li>State the expected variability (precision) explicitly with a <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plus%E2%80%93minus_sign" title=3D"Plus=E2=80=
=93minus sign">plus=E2=80=93minus sign</a>, as in 20&nbsp;000&nbsp;=C2=B1&n=
bsp;1%. This also allows specifying a range of precision in-between powers =
of ten.</li></ul>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Rounding_to_significant_fig=
ures">Rounding to significant figures</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/w/index.php?title=3DSignificant_figures&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=
=3D4" title=3D"Edit section: Rounding to significant figures"><span>edit</s=
pan></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rounding" title=3D"Rounding">Ro=
unding</a> to significant figures is a more general-purpose technique than =
rounding to <i>n</i> digits, since it handles numbers of different scales i=
n a uniform way. For example, the population of a city might only be known =
to the nearest thousand and be stated as 52,000, while the population of a =
country might only be known to the nearest million and be stated as 52,000,=
000. The former might be in error by hundreds, and the latter might be in e=
rror by hundreds of thousands, but both have two significant figures (5 and=
&nbsp;2). This reflects the fact that the significance of the error is the =
same in both cases, relative to the size of the quantity being measured.
</p><p>To round a number to <i>n</i> significant figures:<sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-8" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Significa=
nt_figures#cite_note-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Numerical_Mathemati=
cs_and_Computing,_by_Cheney_and_Kincaid_9-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Significant_figures#cite_note-Numerical_Math=
ematics_and_Computing,_by_Cheney_and_Kincaid-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<ol><li>If the <i>n</i> + 1 digit is greater than 5 or is 5 followed by oth=
er non-zero digits, add 1 to the <i>n</i> digit. For example, if we want to=
 round 1.2459 to 3 significant figures, then this step results in 1.25.</li=
>
<li>If the <i>n</i> + 1 digit is 5 not followed by other digits or followed=
 by only zeros, then rounding requires a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Rounding#Tie-breaking" title=3D"Rounding">tie-breaking</a> rule. For=
 example, to round 1.25 to 2&nbsp;significant figures:
<ul><li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rounding#Round_half_away_f=
rom_zero" title=3D"Rounding">Round half away from zero</a> rounds up to 1.3=
. This is the default rounding method implied in many disciplines<sup class=
=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<=
i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=
=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title=3D"How many, and which, discipli=
nes? (August 2018)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup> if the required r=
ounding method is not specified.</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rounding#Round_half_to_even" t=
itle=3D"Rounding">Round half to even</a>, which rounds to the nearest even =
number. With this method, 1.25 is rounded down to 1.2. If this method appli=
es to 1.35, then it is rounded up to 1.4. This is the method preferred by m=
any scientific disciplines, because, for example, it avoids skewing the ave=
rage value of a long list of values upwards.</li></ul></li>
<li>For an integer in rounding, replace the digits after the <i>n</i> digit=
 with zeros. For example, if 1254 is rounded to 2&nbsp;significant figures,=
 then 5 and 4 are replaced to 0 so that it will be 1300. For a number with =
the decimal point in rounding, remove the digits after the <i>n</i> digit. =
For example, if 14.895 is rounded to 3&nbsp;significant figures, then the d=
igits after 8 are removed so that it will be 14.9.</li></ol>
<p>In financial calculations, a number is often rounded to a given number o=
f places. For example, to two places after the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Decimal_separator" title=3D"Decimal separator">decimal separat=
or</a> for many world currencies. This is done because greater precision is=
 immaterial, and usually it is not possible to settle a debt of less than t=
he smallest currency unit.
</p><p>In UK personal tax returns, income is rounded down to the nearest po=
und, whilst tax paid is calculated to the nearest penny.
</p><p>As an illustration, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dec=
imal" title=3D"Decimal">decimal</a> quantity <b>12.345</b> can be expressed=
 with various numbers of significant figures or decimal places. If insuffic=
ient precision is available then the number is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Rounding" title=3D"Rounding">rounded</a> in some manner to fit=
 the available precision. The following table shows the results for various=
 total precision at two rounding ways (N/A stands for Not Applicable).
</p>
