  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/1a03f96842521cc74af8aefae60402c9529bc7d2" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-display mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertica=
l-align: -0.838ex; width:23.851ex; height:2.843ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle n=
=3D\lfloor \log _{10}(|x|)\rfloor +1-p}"></span>
</p><p>which may need to be written with a specific marking as detailed <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Significant_figures#Significant_figur=
es_rules_explained">above</a> to specify the number of significant trailing=
 zeros.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Writing_uncertainty_and_imp=
lied_uncertainty">Writing uncertainty and implied uncertainty</h2><span cla=
ss=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSignificant_figures&amp;a=
ction=3Dedit&amp;section=3D5" title=3D"Edit section: Writing uncertainty an=
d implied uncertainty"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-b=
racket">]</span></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Significant_figures_in_writ=
ing_uncertainty">Significant figures in writing uncertainty</h3><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSignificant_figures&amp;ac=
tion=3Dedit&amp;section=3D6" title=3D"Edit section: Significant figures in =
writing uncertainty"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bra=
cket">]</span></span></div>
<p>It is recommended for a measurement result to include the measurement un=
certainty such as <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline">=
<span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"displa=
y: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\d=
isplaystyle x_{\text{best}}\pm \sigma _{x}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <msub>
          <mi>x</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mtext>best</mtext>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
        <mo>=C2=B1<!-- =C2=B1 --></mo>
        <msub>
          <mi>=CF=83<!-- =CF=83 --></mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>x</mi>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle x_{\text{best=
}}\pm \sigma _{x}}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/13a8d55282d561020ebb4ad04e001f14b7aba11a" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.671ex; width:9.834ex; height:2.509ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle x_{=
\text{best}}\pm \sigma _{x}}"></span>, where <i>x</i><sub>best</sub> and <i=
>=CF=83<sub>x</sub></i> are the best estimate and uncertainty in the measur=
ement respectively.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-10" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Significant_figures#cite_note-10"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 <i>x</i><sub>best</sub> can be the average of measured values and <i>=CF=
=83<sub>x</sub></i> can be the standard deviation or a multiple of the meas=
urement deviation. The rules to write <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-m=
ath-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a=
11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/Ma=
thML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle x_{\text{best}}\pm \sigma _{x}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <msub>
          <mi>x</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mtext>best</mtext>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
        <mo>=C2=B1<!-- =C2=B1 --></mo>
        <msub>
          <mi>=CF=83<!-- =CF=83 --></mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>x</mi>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle x_{\text{best=
}}\pm \sigma _{x}}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/13a8d55282d561020ebb4ad04e001f14b7aba11a" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.671ex; width:9.834ex; height:2.509ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle x_{=
\text{best}}\pm \sigma _{x}}"></span> are:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-11" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Significant_figures#cit=
e_note-11"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li><i>=CF=83<sub>x</sub></i> should usually be quoted to only one or t=
wo significant figures, as more precision is unlikely to be reliable or mea=
ningful:
<ul><li>1.79 =C2=B1 0.06 (correct), 1.79&nbsp;=C2=B1&nbsp;0.96 (correct), 1=
.79&nbsp;=C2=B1&nbsp;1.96 (incorrect).</li></ul></li>
<li>The digit positions of the last significant figures in <i>x</i><sub>bes=
t</sub> and <i>=CF=83<sub>x</sub></i> are the same, otherwise the consisten=
cy is lost. For example, "1.79&nbsp;=C2=B1 0.067" is incorrect, as it does =
not make sense to have more accurate uncertainty than the best estimate.
<ul><li>1.79 =C2=B1 0.06 (correct), 1.79&nbsp;=C2=B1&nbsp;0.96 (correct), 1=
.79&nbsp;=C2=B1&nbsp;0.067 (incorrect).</li></ul></li></ul>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Implied_uncertainty">Implie=
d uncertainty</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=
=3DSignificant_figures&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D7" title=3D"Edit sec=
tion: Implied uncertainty"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsecti=
on-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Mic_speed_limit.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-descrip=
tion"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/34=
/Mic_speed_limit.jpg/250px-Mic_speed_limit.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D=
"250" height=3D"141" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"1600" dat=
a-file-height=3D"900"></a><figcaption>Persnickety sign implies 14.6 is spee=
d violation</figcaption></figure>
<p>Uncertainty may be implied by the last significant figure if it is not e=
xplicitly expressed.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:0_1-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Significant_figures#cite_note-:0-1"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup> The implied uncertainty is =C2=B1 the half of the minimum scale at th=
e last significant figure position. For example, if the mass of an object i=
s reported as 3.78&nbsp;kg without mentioning uncertainty, then =C2=B1&nbsp=
;0.005&nbsp;kg measurement uncertainty may be implied. If the mass of an ob=
ject is estimated as 3.78 =C2=B1 0.07&nbsp;kg, so the actual mass is probab=
ly somewhere in the range 3.71 to 3.85&nbsp;kg, and it is desired to report=
 it with a single number, then 3.8&nbsp;kg is the best number to report sin=
ce its implied uncertainty =C2=B1&nbsp;0.05&nbsp;kg gives a mass range of 3=
.75 to 3.85&nbsp;kg, which is close to the measurement range. If the uncert=
ainty is a bit larger, i.e. 3.78&nbsp;=C2=B1&nbsp;0.09&nbsp;kg, then 3.8&nb=
sp;kg is still the best single number to quote, since if "4&nbsp;kg" was re=
ported then a lot of information would be lost.
</p><p>If there is a need to write the implied uncertainty of a number, the=
n it can be written as <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inl=
ine"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"d=
isplay: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=
=3D"{\displaystyle x\pm \sigma _{x}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>x</mi>
        <mo>=C2=B1<!-- =C2=B1 --></mo>
        <msub>
          <mi>=CF=83<!-- =CF=83 --></mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>x</mi>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle x\pm \sigma _=
{x}}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/78d5662f0241d9a18f0801f3504971bc310844a7" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.671ex; width:6.67ex; height:2.509ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle x\pm=
 \sigma _{x}}"></span>with stating it as the implied uncertainty (to preven=
t readers from recognizing it as the measurement uncertainty), where <i>x</=
i> and <i>=CF=83<sub>x</sub></i> are the number with an extra zero digit (t=
o follow the rules to write uncertainty above) and the implied uncertainty =
of it respectively. For example, 6&nbsp;kg with the implied uncertainty =C2=
=B1&nbsp;0.5&nbsp;kg can be stated as 6.0&nbsp;=C2=B1&nbsp;0.5&nbsp;kg.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Arithmetic">Arithmetic</h2>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSignificant_figu=
res&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D8" title=3D"Edit section: Arithmetic"><=
span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span><=
/div>
<p>As there are rules to determine the significant figures in directly <i>m=
easured</i> quantities, there are also guidelines (not rules) to determine =
the significant figures in quantities <i>calculated</i> from these <i>measu=
red</i> quantities.
</p><p>Significant figures in <i>measured</i> quantities are most important=
 in the determination of significant figures in <i>calculated quantities</i=
> with them. A mathematical or physical constant (e.g., <span class=3D"texh=
tml">=CF=80</span> in the formula for the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Area_of_a_disk" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Area of a disk">area=
 of a circle</a> with radius <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i></span> as <sp=
an class=3D"texhtml">=CF=80<i>r</i><sup>2</sup></span>) has no effect on th=
e determination of the significant figures in the result of a calculation w=
ith it if its known digits are equal to or more than the significant figure=
s in the measured quantities used in the calculation. An exact number such =
as <span class=3D"texhtml"><span class=3D"sfrac">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"ti=
on"><span class=3D"num">1</span><span class=3D"sr-only">/</span><span class=
=3D"den">2</span></span>=E2=81=A0</span></span> in the formula for the <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kinetic_energy" title=3D"Kinetic energ=
y">kinetic energy</a> of a mass <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>m</i></span> wit=
h velocity <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>v</i></span> as <span class=3D"texhtm=
l"><link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyle=
s:r1214402035"><span class=3D"sfrac">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"tion"><span cl=
ass=3D"num">1</span><span class=3D"sr-only">/</span><span class=3D"den">2</=
span></span>=E2=81=A0</span><i>mv</i><sup>2</sup></span> has no bearing on =
the significant figures in the calculated kinetic energy since its number o=
f significant figures is infinite (0.500000...).
</p><p>The guidelines described below are intended to avoid a calculation r=
esult more precise than the measured quantities, but it does not ensure the=
 resulted implied uncertainty close enough to the measured uncertainties. T=
his problem can be seen in unit conversion. If the guidelines give the impl=
ied uncertainty too far from the measured ones, then it may be needed to de=
cide significant digits that give comparable uncertainty.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Multiplication_and_division=
">Multiplication and division</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/=
index.php?title=3DSignificant_figures&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D9" ti=
tle=3D"Edit section: Multiplication and division"><span>edit</span></a><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>For quantities created from measured quantities via <b>multiplication</b=
> and <b>division</b>, the calculated result should have as many significan=
t figures as the <i>least</i> number of significant figures among the measu=
red quantities used in the calculation.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-12" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Significant_figures#cite_n=
ote-12"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup> For example,=20
</p>
<dl><dd><ul><li>1.234 =C3=97 2 =3D <span style=3D"text-decoration:overline;=
">2</span>.468 =E2=89=88 2</li>
<li>1.234 =C3=97 2.0 =3D 2.<span style=3D"text-decoration:overline;">4</spa=
n>68 =E2=89=88 2.5</li>
<li>0.01234 =C3=97 2 =3D 0.0<span style=3D"text-decoration:overline;">2</sp=
an>468 =E2=89=88 0.02</li>
<li>0.012345678 / 0.00234 =3D 5.2<span style=3D"text-decoration:overline;">=
7</span>59 =E2=89=88 5.28</li></ul></dd></dl>
<p>with <i>one</i>, <i>two</i>, and <i>one</i> significant figures respecti=
vely. (2 here is assumed not an exact number.) For the first example, the f=
irst multiplication factor has four significant figures and the second has =
one significant figure. The factor with the fewest or least significant fig=
ures is the second one with only one, so the final calculated result should=
 also have one significant figure.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Exception">Exception</h4><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSignificant_figure=
s&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D10" title=3D"Edit section: Exception"><sp=
an>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></d=
iv>
<p>For unit conversion, the implied uncertainty of the result can be unsati=
sfactorily higher than that in the previous unit if this rounding guideline=
 is followed; For example, 8&nbsp;inches has the implied uncertainty of =C2=
=B1&nbsp;0.5&nbsp;inch =3D =C2=B1&nbsp;1.27&nbsp;cm. If it is converted to =
the centimeter scale and the rounding guideline for multiplication and divi=
sion is followed, then <span style=3D"text-decoration:overline;">2</span>0.=
32&nbsp;cm =E2=89=88 20&nbsp;cm with the implied uncertainty of =C2=B1&nbsp=
;5&nbsp;cm. If this implied uncertainty is considered as too overestimated,=
 then more proper significant digits in the unit conversion result may be 2=
<span style=3D"text-decoration:overline;">0</span>.32&nbsp;cm =E2=89=88 20.=
&nbsp;cm with the implied uncertainty of =C2=B1&nbsp;0.5&nbsp;cm.
</p><p>Another exception of applying the above rounding guideline is to mul=
tiply a number by an integer, such as 1.234 =C3=97&nbsp;9. If the above gui=
deline is followed, then the result is rounded as 1.234 =C3=97 9.000.... =
=3D 11.1<span style=3D"text-decoration:overline;">0</span>6 =E2=89=88 11.11=
. However, this multiplication is essentially adding 1.234 to itself 9 time=
s such as 1.234 + 1.234 + =E2=80=A6 + 1.234 so the rounding guideline for a=
ddition and subtraction described below is more proper rounding approach.<s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-13" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Significant_figures#cite_note-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> As a result, the fina=
l answer is 1.234 + 1.234 + =E2=80=A6 + 1.234 =3D 11.10<span style=3D"text-=
decoration:overline;">6</span> =3D 11.106 (one significant digit increase).
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Addition_and_subtraction_of=
_significant_figures">Addition and subtraction of significant figures</h3><=
span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</spa=
n><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSignificant_figur=
es&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D11" title=3D"Edit section: Addition and =
subtraction of significant figures"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-=
editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>For quantities created from measured quantities via <b>addition</b> and =
<b>subtraction</b>, the last significant figure position (e.g., hundreds, t=
ens, ones, tenths, hundredths, and so forth) in the calculated result shoul=
d be the same as the <i>leftmost</i> or largest digit position among the la=
st significant figures of the <i>measured</i> quantities in the calculation=
. For example,=20
</p>
<dl><dd><ul><li>1.234 + 2 =3D <span style=3D"text-decoration:overline;">3</=
span>.234 =E2=89=88 3</li>
<li>1.234 + 2.0 =3D 3.<span style=3D"text-decoration:overline;">2</span>34 =
=E2=89=88 3.2</li>
<li>0.01234 + 2 =3D <span style=3D"text-decoration:overline;">2</span>.0123=
4 =E2=89=88 2</li>
<li>12000 + 77 =3D 1<span style=3D"text-decoration:overline;">2</span>077 =
=E2=89=88 12000</li></ul></dd></dl>
<p>with the last significant figures in the <i>ones</i> place, <i>tenths</i=
> place, <i>ones</i> place, and <i>thousands</i> place respectively. (2 her=
e is assumed not an exact number.) For the first example, the first term ha=
s its last significant figure in the thousandths place and the second term =
has its last significant figure in the <i>ones</i> place. The leftmost or l=
argest digit position among the last significant figures of these terms is =
the ones place, so the calculated result should also have its last signific=
ant figure in the ones place.
</p><p>The rule to calculate significant figures for multiplication and div=
ision are not the same as the rule for addition and subtraction. For multip=
lication and division, only the total number of significant figures in each=
 of the factors in the calculation matters; the digit position of the last =
significant figure in each factor is irrelevant. For addition and subtracti=
on, only the digit position of the last significant figure in each of the t=
erms in the calculation matters; the total number of significant figures in=
 each term is irrelevant.<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fac=
t" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span tit=
le=3D"This claim needs references to reliable sources. (July 2020)">citatio=
n needed</span></a></i>]</sup>  However, greater accuracy will often be obt=
ained if some non-significant digits are maintained in intermediate results=
 which are used in subsequent calculations.<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Tem=
plate Template-Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation=
 needed"><span title=3D"This claim needs references to reliable sources. (J=
uly 2020)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Logarithm_and_antilogarithm=
">Logarithm and antilogarithm</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/=
index.php?title=3DSignificant_figures&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D12" t=
itle=3D"Edit section: Logarithm and antilogarithm"><span>edit</span></a><sp=
an class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Base_of_a_logarithm" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Base of a logarithm">base</a>-10 <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm" title=3D"Logarithm">logarithm</a> of a =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Normalized_number" title=3D"Normal=
ized number">normalized number</a> (i.e., <i>a</i> =C3=97 10<sup><i>b</i></=
sup> with 1 =E2=89=A4 <i>a</i> &lt; 10 and <i>b</i> as an integer), is roun=
ded such that its decimal part (called <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Mantissa_(logarithm)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Mantissa (logarit=
hm)">mantissa</a>) has as many significant figures as the significant figur=
es in the normalized number.
</p>
<ul><li>log<sub>10</sub>(3.000 =C3=97 10<sup>4</sup>) =3D log<sub>10</sub>(=
10<sup>4</sup>) + log<sub>10</sub>(3.000) =3D 4.000000... (exact number so =
infinite significant digits) + 0.477<span style=3D"text-decoration:overline=
;">1</span>212547... =3D 4.477<span style=3D"text-decoration:overline;">1</=
span>212547 =E2=89=88 4.4771.</li></ul>
<p>When taking the antilogarithm of a normalized number, the result is roun=
ded to have as many significant figures as the significant figures in the d=
ecimal part of the number to be antiloged.
</p>
<ul><li>10<sup>4.4771</sup> =3D 299<span style=3D"text-decoration:overline;=
">9</span>8.5318119... =3D 30000 =3D 3.000 =C3=97 10<sup>4</sup>.</li></ul>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Transcendental_functions">T=
ranscendental functions</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"m=
