<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Round_only_on_the_final_cal=
culation_result">Round only on the final calculation result</h3><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSignificant_figures&amp;ac=
tion=3Dedit&amp;section=3D14" title=3D"Edit section: Round only on the fina=
l calculation result"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">]</span></span></div>
<p>When performing multiple stage calculations, do not round intermediate s=
tage calculation results; keep as many digits as is practical (at least one=
 more digit than the rounding rule allows per stage) until the end of all t=
he calculations to avoid cumulative rounding errors while tracking or recor=
ding the significant figures in each intermediate result. Then, round the f=
inal result, for example, to the fewest number of significant figures (for =
multiplication or division) or leftmost last significant digit position (fo=
r addition or subtraction) among the inputs in the final calculation.<sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-14" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Significant_figures#cite_note-14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li>(2.3494 + 1.345) =C3=97 1.2 =3D 3.69<span style=3D"text-decoration:=
overline;">4</span>4 =C3=97 1.2 =3D 4.<span style=3D"text-decoration:overli=
ne;">4</span>3328  =E2=89=88 4.4.</li>
<li>(2.3494 =C3=97 1.345) + 1.2 =3D 3.15<span style=3D"text-decoration:over=
line;">9</span>943 + 1.2 =3D 4.<span style=3D"text-decoration:overline;">3<=
/span>59943  =E2=89=88 4.4.</li></ul>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Estimating_an_extra_digit">=
Estimating an extra digit</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D=
"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/inde=
x.php?title=3DSignificant_figures&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D15" title=
=3D"Edit section: Estimating an extra digit"><span>edit</span></a><span cla=
ss=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>When using a ruler, initially use the smallest mark as the first estimat=
ed digit. For example, if a ruler's smallest mark is 0.1&nbsp;cm, and 4.5&n=
bsp;cm is read, then it is 4.5 (=C2=B10.1&nbsp;cm) or 4.4&nbsp;cm to 4.6&nb=
sp;cm as to the smallest mark interval. However, in practice a measurement =
can usually be estimated by eye to closer than the interval between the rul=
er's smallest mark, e.g. in the above case it might be estimated as between=
 4.51&nbsp;cm and 4.53&nbsp;cm.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-UMmeasurements_15-0" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Significant_figur=
es#cite_note-UMmeasurements-15"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>It is also possible that the overall length of a ruler may not be ac=
curate to the degree of the smallest mark, and the marks may be imperfectly=
 spaced within each unit. However assuming a normal good quality ruler, it =
should be possible to estimate tenths between the nearest two marks to achi=
eve an extra decimal place of accuracy.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Weston_16-0" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Significant_figur=
es#cite_note-Weston-16"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>16<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Failing to do this adds the error in r=
eading the ruler to any error in the calibration of the ruler.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Estimation_in_statistic">Es=
timation in statistic</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-=
editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.ph=
p?title=3DSignificant_figures&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D16" title=3D"=
Edit section: Estimation in statistic"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"=
mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Estimation" title=3D=
"Estimation">Estimation</a></div>
<p>When estimating the proportion of individuals carrying some particular c=
haracteristic in a population, from a random sample of that population, the=
 number of significant figures should not exceed the maximum precision allo=
wed by that sample size.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Relationship_to_accuracy_an=
d_precision_in_measurement">Relationship to accuracy and precision in measu=
rement</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bra=
cket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSigni=
ficant_figures&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D17" title=3D"Edit section: R=
elationship to accuracy and precision in measurement"><span>edit</span></a>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accuracy_and_precisi=
on" title=3D"Accuracy and precision">Accuracy and precision</a></div>
<p>Traditionally, in various technical fields, "accuracy" refers to the clo=
seness of a given measurement to its true value; "precision" refers to the =
stability of that measurement when repeated many times. Thus, it is possibl=
e to be "precisely wrong".  Hoping to reflect the way in which the term "ac=
curacy" is actually used in the scientific community, there is a recent sta=
ndard, ISO&nbsp;5725, which keeps the same definition of precision but defi=
nes the term "trueness" as the closeness of a given measurement to its true=
 value and uses the term "accuracy" as the combination of trueness and prec=
ision.  (See the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accuracy_and_prec=
ision" title=3D"Accuracy and precision">accuracy and precision</a> article =
for a full discussion.)  In either case, the number of significant figures =
roughly corresponds to <i>precision</i>, not to accuracy or the newer conce=
pt of trueness.=20
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"In_computing">In computing<=
/h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[=
</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSignificant_=
figures&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D18" title=3D"Edit section: In compu=
ting"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span><=
/span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Floating-point_arith=
metic" title=3D"Floating-point arithmetic">Floating-point arithmetic</a></d=
iv>
<p>Computer representations of floating-point numbers use a form of roundin=
g to significant figures (while usually not keeping track of how many), in =
general with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_number" title=
=3D"Binary number">binary numbers</a>. The number of correct significant fi=
gures is closely related to the notion of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Approximation_error" title=3D"Approximation error">relative error</=
a> (which has the advantage of being a more accurate measure of precision, =
and is independent of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radix" t=
itle=3D"Radix">radix</a>, also known as the base, of the number system used=
).
</p><p><span class=3D"anchor" id=3D"Sig-fig_calculator"></span>Electronic c=
alculators supporting a dedicated significant figures display mode are rela=
tively rare.
</p><p>Among the calculators to support related features are the <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Commodore_Business_Machines" class=3D"mw-red=
irect" title=3D"Commodore Business Machines">Commodore</a> <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCommodore_M55&amp;action=3Dedit&amp=
;redlink=3D1" class=3D"new" title=3D"Commodore M55 (page does not exist)">M=
55 Mathematician</a> (1976)<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Commodore_M55_17-0" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Significant_figures#ci=
te_note-Commodore_M55-17"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>17<span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCommodore_S61&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;redlink=3D1"=
 class=3D"new" title=3D"Commodore S61 (page does not exist)">S61 Statistici=
an</a> (1976),<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Commodore_S61_18-0" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Significant_figures#cite_note-Commo=
dore_S61-18"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>18<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup> which support two display modes, where <kbd class=
=3D"keyboard-key nowrap">DISP</kbd>+<kbd class=3D"keyboard-key nowrap"><i>n=
</i></kbd> will give <i>n</i> significant digits in total, while <link rel=
=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r124918286=
8"><kbd class=3D"keyboard-key nowrap">DISP</kbd>+<kbd class=3D"keyboard-key=
 nowrap">.</kbd>+<kbd class=3D"keyboard-key nowrap"><i>n</i></kbd> will giv=
e <i>n</i> decimal places.
</p><p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Texas_Instruments" titl=
e=3D"Texas Instruments">Texas Instruments</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/TI-83_Plus" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"TI-83 Plus">TI-83 Pl=
us</a> (1999) and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/TI-84_Plus" clas=
s=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"TI-84 Plus">TI-84 Plus</a> (2004) families of <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Graphical_calculator" class=3D"mw-re=
direct" title=3D"Graphical calculator">graphical calculators</a> support a =
<i>Sig-Fig Calculator</i> mode in which the calculator will evaluate the co=
unt of significant digits of entered numbers and display it in square brack=
ets behind the corresponding number. The results of calculations will be ad=
justed to only show the significant digits as well.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-TI_2=
023_19-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sign=
ificant_figures#cite_note-TI_2023-19"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
19<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>For the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hewlett-Packard" ti=
tle=3D"Hewlett-Packard">HP</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HP_=
